<article>
    <h1>Some&#xAD;thing nice, some&#xAD;thing with spice</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200824/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-08-24"><time>2020-08-24</time></a>
        - <span>CLASSIFIED&#xAD;S</span>
        - <span role="byline">JUSTIN CHUA</span>
    </section>

    <p>Just what is it about In­dian food that makes it such a go-to? Come break­fast or sup­per, and any­thing in be­tween, these evoca­tive dishes seem to have a dis­tinct way of lur­ing us in. What comes to mind at the mere men­tion of In­dian food is spice. But not tongue-numb­ing, tear-jerk­ing spice, per se. The spices present in each dish seem to serve their own unique pur­pose, com­ple­ment­ing the oth­ers to pamper the taste buds.</p>
    <p>Thank­fully, we have plenty of restau­rants and eater­ies that spe­cialise in this mag­nif­i­cent cui­sine. Let’s take a look at a cou­ple.</p>
    <p>Hav­ing fea­tured on the Miche­lin Guide in 2016 and adorned with mul­ti­ple in­dus­try awards, Zaf­fron Kitchen stands out right off the bat. If you con­sider your­self a con­nois­seur of the cui­sine, then you may have heard of them. Where au­then­tic In­dian cui­sine meets lo­cal flavours, you will find no short­age of flavours on of­fer here.</p>
    <p>Al Hus­sain Restau­rant is an­other place wor­thy of your pa­tron­age. Serv­ing up In­dian and Thai food round the clock, they don’t ex­actly make it easy for you to say no. But say yes and you in­vite a wealth of lip-smack­ing de­lights into your tummy. How does that sound?</p>

